00:26:56,298 --> 00:27:00,588
Oh, Judge Wilson, forgive me,
but how can anyone see you

506
00:27:00,678 --> 00:27:04,638
if you insist on standing
in Mr. Dickinson's shadow?

507
00:27:05,850 --> 00:27:09,810
James Wilson,
also of Pennsylvania.

508
00:27:09,895 --> 00:27:10,975
Sir.

509
00:27:12,356 --> 00:27:13,856
An honor, sir.

510
00:27:14,692 --> 00:27:16,822
FRANKLlN: Good morning.
Good morning.

511
00:27:19,572 --> 00:27:21,702
Good morning, ladies.
Good morning.

512
00:27:21,782 --> 00:27:23,322
Steady, steady.

513
00:27:24,952 --> 00:27:27,662
MAN: Make gangway, sir.
Make gangway!

514
00:27:27,746 --> 00:27:29,996
Good morning,
Mr. Wilson. Good morning.

515
00:27:30,082 --> 00:27:33,082
Watch where
you're going, damn it.
Over there.

516
00:27:33,461 --> 00:27:36,421
McNair, get me
out of this thing.

517
00:27:36,505 --> 00:27:38,625
Watch out for my foot.

518
00:27:38,716 --> 00:27:39,836
Good morning, all.

519
00:27:39,925 --> 00:27:41,885
Morning, Ben.
ALL: Morning, Ben.

520
00:27:42,219 --> 00:27:43,679
Here you are.
Two coppers apiece.

521
00:27:43,762 --> 00:27:45,562
Now, straight back
to jail with you.

522
00:27:45,639 --> 00:27:47,769
Good morning, Stephen.
All right, Benjamin.

523
00:27:47,850 --> 00:27:49,230
(GROANS)

524
00:27:49,310 --> 00:27:50,560
Dear God.

525
00:27:53,272 --> 00:27:54,652
What are you staring at?

526
00:27:54,732 --> 00:27:56,942
Haven't you ever seen
a great man before?

527
00:27:57,026 --> 00:27:59,316
Good Lord, sir.
Do you have the honor
to be Dr. Franklin?

528
00:27:59,403 --> 00:28:00,453
Yes, l have that honor.

529
00:28:00,529 --> 00:28:03,359
Unfortunately, the gout
accompanies the honor.

530
00:28:03,449 --> 00:28:04,949
Been living
too high again, eh, pappy?

531
00:28:05,034 --> 00:28:08,704
Oh, Stephen, l only wish
King George felt like
my big toe all over.

532
00:28:08,787 --> 00:28:10,657
(LAUGHS)

533
00:28:10,748 --> 00:28:14,498
McNair! Fetch a pillow
and two more rums.

534
00:28:14,585 --> 00:28:15,955
Well, Franklin,
where's that idiot Lee?

535
00:28:16,045 --> 00:28:17,665
ls he back yet?
l don't see him.

536
00:28:17,755 --> 00:28:20,505
Softly, John. Your voice
is hurting my foot.

537
00:28:20,591 --> 00:28:22,051
One more day, Franklin.
That's how long

538
00:28:22,134 --> 00:28:24,184
l'll remain silent,
not a minute longer.

539
00:28:24,261 --> 00:28:26,801
That strutting popinjay
was so damn sure of himself.

540
00:28:26,889 --> 00:28:29,099
He's had time to bring back
a dozen proposals by now.

541
00:28:29,183 --> 00:28:30,233
Tell me, James.

542
00:28:30,309 --> 00:28:33,649
How do you
explain the strange,
monumental quietude

543
00:28:33,729 --> 00:28:36,229
that Congress
has been treated to
these past 30 days?

544
00:28:36,315 --> 00:28:39,935
Has the ill wind
of independence
finally blown itself out?

545
00:28:40,819 --> 00:28:42,649
Well, if you ask me. . .

546
00:28:42,738 --> 00:28:46,408
For myself, l must confess
that a month free
from New England noise

547
00:28:46,492 --> 00:28:48,452
is more therapeutic
than a month in the country.

548
00:28:48,536 --> 00:28:50,156
Don't you agree, James?

549
00:28:50,246 --> 00:28:51,366
Well, l feel. . .

550
00:28:51,455 --> 00:28:53,495
Mr. Adams, pray look
for your voice, sir.

551
00:28:53,582 --> 00:28:56,212
lt cannot be far,
and God knows we need

552
00:28:56,293 --> 00:28:58,213
the entertainment
in Congress.

553
00:28:58,295 --> 00:28:59,745
(ALL LAUGHlNG)

554
00:29:02,466 --> 00:29:03,676
Congratulations, John.

555
00:29:03,759 --> 00:29:05,719
You just made your greatest
contribution to independence.

556
00:29:05,803 --> 00:29:07,103
You kept your flap shut.

557
00:29:07,179 --> 00:29:08,599
One more day, Franklin.

558
00:29:08,681 --> 00:29:10,931
Then l shall do
the proposing.

559
00:29:12,268 --> 00:29:15,978
Gentlemen, the usual morning
festivities concluded,

560
00:29:16,063 --> 00:29:18,483
l will now call
Congress to order.

561
00:29:18,899 --> 00:29:20,399
Mr. Thomson.

562
00:29:23,988 --> 00:29:25,278
The Second Continental
Congress meeting

563
00:29:25,364 --> 00:29:27,624
in the city of Philadelphia
is now in session.

564
00:29:27,700 --> 00:29:31,240
7 June, 1 776,
the 380th meeting.

565
00:29:31,328 --> 00:29:32,948
Sweet Jesus!

566
00:29:34,790 --> 00:29:38,130
The Honorable John Hancock
of Massachusetts Bay,
president.

567
00:29:40,170 --> 00:29:43,050
Thank you,
Mr. Thomson.
Mr. McNair.

568
00:29:43,132 --> 00:29:46,472
The stores of rum
and other drinking spirits
are hereby closed

569
00:29:46,552 --> 00:29:50,052
to the colony of Rhode lsland
for a period of three days.

570
00:29:50,139 --> 00:29:51,509
Yes, sir.

571
00:29:51,599 --> 00:29:53,389
(MEN RAPPlNG ON TABLES)
Johnny, you can't do that.

572
00:29:53,475 --> 00:29:56,765
Sit down, Mr. Hopkins.
You've abused the privilege.

573
00:29:57,563 --> 00:29:59,193
(MEN LAUGHlNG)

574
00:29:59,273 --> 00:30:01,153
The chair would like
to take this opportunity

575
00:30:01,233 --> 00:30:04,193
to welcome
Dr. Lyman Hall of Georgia
to this Congress,

576
00:30:04,278 --> 00:30:06,278
and hopes he will make
the best of it.

577
00:30:09,491 --> 00:30:11,371
My God, it's hot.

578
00:30:12,369 --> 00:30:14,579
The secretary
will read the roll.

579
00:30:14,663 --> 00:30:16,913
All members present
with the following
exceptions.

580
00:30:17,458 --> 00:30:20,248
"Mr. Paine, Mr. Gerry,
Mr. Samuel Adams
of Massachusetts,

581
00:30:20,336 --> 00:30:21,996
"Mr. Morton of Pennsylvania,

582
00:30:22,129 --> 00:30:24,339
"Mr. Wythe and
Mr. Richard Henry Lee
of Virginia."

583
00:30:24,840 --> 00:30:27,590
And the entire delegation
of New Jersey.

584
00:30:28,010 --> 00:30:29,840
l'm concerned over
the continual absence

585
00:30:29,928 --> 00:30:33,058
of one-thirteenth
of this Congress.
Where is New Jersey?

586
00:30:33,474 --> 00:30:36,354
Somewhere between
New York and Pennsylvania.

587
00:30:36,935 --> 00:30:38,595
(ALL LAUGHlNG)

588
00:30:39,855 --> 00:30:41,605
Thank you very much.

589
00:30:42,358 --> 00:30:46,148
Dr. Franklin,
have you heard anything?
Your son resides there.

590
00:30:46,236 --> 00:30:47,486
Son, sir? What son?

591
00:30:48,447 --> 00:30:51,067
The royal governor
of New Jersey, sir.

592
00:30:51,784 --> 00:30:53,794
As that title
might suggest, sir,

593
00:30:53,869 --> 00:30:56,199
we are not in touch
at the present time.

594
00:30:56,622 --> 00:30:58,462
Yes. Well. . .

595
00:30:59,041 --> 00:31:00,961
Now for the weather report,

596
00:31:01,043 --> 00:31:03,043
Mr. Jefferson of Virginia.

597
00:31:05,339 --> 00:31:06,339
Mr. Jefferson !

598
00:31:07,424 --> 00:31:08,554
Present, sir.

599
00:31:09,093 --> 00:31:10,723
May we hear
about the weather?

600
00:31:11,011 --> 00:31:13,601
As if it weren't
speaking for itself.

601
00:31:15,224 --> 00:31:17,814
Eighty-seven degrees
of temperature,

602
00:31:17,893 --> 00:31:20,903
thirty-point-aught-six
inches of mercury.

603
00:31:21,522 --> 00:31:22,732
Wind. . .

604
00:31:23,774 --> 00:31:26,114
From the southwest
for the rest of the day.

605
00:31:26,193 --> 00:31:27,653
And tonight. . .

606
00:31:27,736 --> 00:31:29,986
Tonight l'm leaving for home.

607
00:31:30,072 --> 00:31:31,532
On business?

608
00:31:31,615 --> 00:31:32,695
Family business.

609
00:31:32,950 --> 00:31:35,540
Give her a flourish for me,
young feller.

610
00:31:35,786 --> 00:31:37,076
(ALL LAUGHlNG)

611
00:31:40,165 --> 00:31:41,325
Whoa!

612
00:32:03,272 --> 00:32:05,902
"From the Commander,
army of the United Colonies
to New York,

613
00:32:05,983 --> 00:32:08,363
"dispatch number 1 , 1 37."

614
00:32:08,444 --> 00:32:10,614
Ah, sweet Jesus!

615
00:32:11,113 --> 00:32:12,703
"To the Honorable Congress,
John Hancock, president.

616
00:32:12,781 --> 00:32:16,531
"Dear sir,
it is with grave apprehension
that l have learned this day

617
00:32:16,618 --> 00:32:18,748
"of the sailing from Halifax,
Nova Scotia,

618
00:32:18,829 --> 00:32:20,659
"of a considerable force
of British troops

619
00:32:20,748 --> 00:32:22,248
"in the company of
foreign mercenaries

620
00:32:22,332 --> 00:32:24,922
"and under the command
of General Sir William Howe."

621
00:32:25,002 --> 00:32:27,462
"There can be no doubt
that their destination
is New York,

622
00:32:27,546 --> 00:32:30,716
"for to take
and hold this city
and the Hudson Valley beyond

623
00:32:30,799 --> 00:32:33,629
"would serve to
separate New England from
the rest of the colonies,

624
00:32:33,719 --> 00:32:36,759
"permitting both sections
to be crushed in turn.

625
00:32:36,847 --> 00:32:39,427
"Sadly, l see no way
of stopping them
at the present time,

626
00:32:39,516 --> 00:32:41,886
"as my army is
absolutely falling apart.

627
00:32:41,977 --> 00:32:43,977
"My military chest
is totally exhausted.

628
00:32:44,062 --> 00:32:47,322
"My commissary general
has strained his credit
to the last.

629
00:32:47,399 --> 00:32:50,989
"My quartermaster
has no food, no arms,
no ammunition,

630
00:32:51,111 --> 00:32:54,031
"and my troops are in
a state of near mutiny.

631
00:32:54,114 --> 00:32:55,994
"l pray God
some relief arrives

632
00:32:56,074 --> 00:32:58,994
"before the armada,
but fear it will not.

633
00:32:59,077 --> 00:33:00,617
"Your obedient,

634
00:33:01,997 --> 00:33:03,407
"G. Washington."

635
00:33:04,208 --> 00:33:05,748
Mr. President!

636
00:33:05,834 --> 00:33:06,834
Colonel McKean.

637
00:33:06,919 --> 00:33:09,499
Surely we have
managed to promote

638
00:33:09,588 --> 00:33:13,718
the gloomiest man
on this continent
to the head of our troops.

639
00:33:13,801 --> 00:33:18,101
Those dispatches
are the most
depressing accumulation

640
00:33:18,180 --> 00:33:23,480
of disaster, doom and despair
in the entire annals
of military history.

641
00:33:24,186 --> 00:33:26,266
Colonel McKean, please!

642
00:33:26,355 --> 00:33:27,355
What?

643
00:33:28,357 --> 00:33:29,857
lt's too hot.

644
00:33:31,068 --> 00:33:32,818
Well, l suppose so.

645
00:33:33,695 --> 00:33:37,905
General Washington
will continue wording his
dispatches as he sees fit.

646
00:33:37,991 --> 00:33:39,951
And l'm sure we all pray

647
00:33:40,035 --> 00:33:43,955
he finds happier thoughts
to convey in the near future.

648
00:33:45,290 --> 00:33:47,120
Mr. Thomson,
are there any resolutions?

649
00:33:47,543 --> 00:33:49,713
Dr. Josiah Bartlett
of New Hampshire.

650
00:33:51,004 --> 00:33:54,174
"Resolved,
that for the duration
of the present hostilities,

651
00:33:54,258 --> 00:33:57,638
"the Congress discourage
every type of extravagance
and dissipation,

652
00:33:57,719 --> 00:34:00,349
"elaborate funerals
and other
expensive diversions,

653
00:34:00,430 --> 00:34:03,350
"especially all
horse racing, gambling,

654
00:34:03,433 --> 00:34:06,103
"and other forms of
sinful activity, which. . ."

655
00:34:06,186 --> 00:34:07,646
Fire wagon !

656
00:34:08,313 --> 00:34:09,733
(ALL CLAMORlNG)

657
00:34:24,830 --> 00:34:26,410
Where's the fire?
Can anybody tell?

658
00:34:26,498 --> 00:34:27,788
Looks like
the Pemberton House.

659
00:34:27,875 --> 00:34:29,125
lt couldn't be.
lt's brand new.

660
00:34:29,209 --> 00:34:30,839
lt might be the city tavern.

661
00:34:30,919 --> 00:34:32,589
Bite your tongue, man.

662
00:34:35,465 --> 00:34:38,835
LEE: Whoo-hoo!

663
00:34:41,930 --> 00:34:43,310
Benjy, l'm back!

664
00:34:43,932 --> 00:34:45,272
l'm back, Johnny!

665
00:34:45,350 --> 00:34:47,020
Richard, lad,
welcome back.

666
00:34:48,770 --> 00:34:50,190
(LEE WHOOPlNG)

667
00:34:50,898 --> 00:34:51,898
Lee, is it done?

668
00:34:51,982 --> 00:34:53,772
First things first. Tom !

669
00:34:53,859 --> 00:34:58,239
Tom ! Tom, your little
bride wants to know,
"When's he coming home?"

670
00:34:58,322 --> 00:34:59,412
l leave tonight.

671
00:34:59,489 --> 00:35:01,029
Never mind that, man.
ls it done?

672
00:35:01,116 --> 00:35:03,276
Done? Why, certain-Lee.

673
00:35:04,119 --> 00:35:07,869
Mr. President, l have
returned from Virginia with
the following resolution,

674
00:35:07,956 --> 00:35:11,496
"Resolved, that these
united colonies are,
and of a right ought to be,

675
00:35:11,585 --> 00:35:13,035
"free and independent states,

676
00:35:13,128 --> 00:35:15,838
"that they are absolved
from allegiance to
the British Crown,

677
00:35:15,923 --> 00:35:17,553
"and that all political
connection between them

678
00:35:17,633 --> 00:35:19,303
"and the state of
Great Britain is,

679
00:35:19,384 --> 00:35:22,054
"and ought to be,
totally dissolved."

680
00:35:22,137 --> 00:35:23,297
Hear, hear!

681
00:35:23,388 --> 00:35:26,178
Mr. President,
l second the proposal.

682
00:35:26,266 --> 00:35:28,136
The resolution
has been proposed
and seconded.

683
00:35:28,226 --> 00:35:30,766
The chair will now
entertain debate.

684
00:35:31,688 --> 00:35:33,308
Mr. Dickinson.
Mr. President.

685
00:35:33,607 --> 00:35:35,727
Pennsylvania moves,
as always,

686
00:35:35,817 --> 00:35:39,947
that the question
of independence be
postponed indefinitely.

687
00:35:40,030 --> 00:35:41,820
l second the motion.

688
00:35:42,282 --> 00:35:43,742
Judge Wilson,

689
00:35:44,326 --> 00:35:47,076
in your eagerness to be loved,
you seem to have forgotten

690
00:35:47,162 --> 00:35:50,122
that Pennsylvania
cannot second its own motion.

691
00:35:51,541 --> 00:35:53,251
Delaware seconds.

692
00:35:53,335 --> 00:35:55,625
You would, you lousy wart.

693
00:35:56,171 --> 00:35:59,341
The motion to postpone
has been moved and seconded.

694
00:35:59,424 --> 00:36:00,844
Mr. Thomson.

695
00:36:02,344 --> 00:36:04,144
On the motion to
postpone indefinitely

696
00:36:04,221 --> 00:36:07,061
the resolution
on independency
or proceed with the debate,

697
00:36:07,140 --> 00:36:08,810
all those in favor
of debate say "yea,"

698
00:36:08,892 --> 00:36:10,432
all those for
postponement say "nay."

699
00:36:10,519 --> 00:36:11,599
New Hampshire?

700
00:36:12,521 --> 00:36:14,731
New Hampshire favors debate,
and says yea.

701
00:36:17,025 --> 00:36:19,395
New Hampshire says yea.
Massachusetts?

702
00:36:19,778 --> 00:36:24,278
Massachusetts,
having borne the brunt
of the King's tyranny. . .

703
00:36:24,366 --> 00:36:26,366
(ALL CLAMORlNG)
Yes, l said tyranny!

704
00:36:27,119 --> 00:36:30,119
Massachusetts now,
and for all time, says yea.

705
00:36:31,707 --> 00:36:33,537
Massachusetts says yea.

706
00:36:33,875 --> 00:36:35,375
Rhode lsland?

707
00:36:36,378 --> 00:36:37,798
Mr. Hopkins?

708
00:36:38,547 --> 00:36:39,917
Where's Rhode lsland?

709
00:36:40,007 --> 00:36:42,967
Rhode lsland is out
visiting the necessary.

710
00:36:43,260 --> 00:36:46,600
After what
Rhode lsland's consumed,
l can't say l'm surprised.

711
00:36:46,680 --> 00:36:48,600
We'll come back to him,
Mr. Thomson.

712
00:36:48,682 --> 00:36:50,432
Rhode lsland passes.

713
00:36:50,809 --> 00:36:52,019
(ALL LAUGHlNG)

714
00:36:55,188 --> 00:36:56,308
Connecticut?

715
00:36:58,400 --> 00:37:00,990
While Connecticut has,
till now,

716
00:37:01,069 --> 00:37:03,319
been against this proposal,

717
00:37:03,905 --> 00:37:06,365
our legislature
has instructed me
that in the event

718
00:37:06,450 --> 00:37:09,660
it is introduced by
any colony outside
of New England,

719
00:37:09,745 --> 00:37:13,115
we could not any longer
withhold our support.
Connecticut says yea.

720
00:37:13,206 --> 00:37:14,326
Hear! Hear!

721
00:37:14,416 --> 00:37:16,746
Connecticut says yea.
New York?

722
00:37:18,253 --> 00:37:20,673
New York
abstains courteously.

723
00:37:20,922 --> 00:37:22,422
New York abstains.

724
00:37:22,507 --> 00:37:23,547
Courteously.

725
00:37:25,761 --> 00:37:26,841
New Jersey?

726
00:37:26,928 --> 00:37:28,348
Absent, Mr. Secretary.

727
00:37:30,432 --> 00:37:32,312
New Jersey's absent.
Pennsylvania?

728
00:37:33,101 --> 00:37:36,651
Pennsylvania,
for the 24th time, says nay.

729
00:37:36,730 --> 00:37:38,900
Pennsylvania says nay.
Delaware?

730
00:37:39,941 --> 00:37:44,701
Delaware, as ever
for independence, says yea.

731
00:37:44,780 --> 00:37:47,200
Delaware says yea.
Maryland?

732
00:37:48,116 --> 00:37:51,486
Maryland would
welcome independence
if it were given,

733
00:37:51,578 --> 00:37:54,788
but is highly skeptical
that it can be taken.

734
00:37:54,873 --> 00:37:56,543
Maryland says nay.

735
00:37:58,335 --> 00:38:00,535
Maryland says nay.
Virginia?

736
00:38:00,629 --> 00:38:03,379
Virginia, the first colony,
says yea!

737
00:38:06,718 --> 00:38:09,048
Virginia says yea.
North Carolina?

738
00:38:09,137 --> 00:38:13,427
North Carolina
respectfully yields
to South Carolina.

739
00:38:13,517 --> 00:38:14,557
South Carolina?

740
00:38:14,643 --> 00:38:16,143
Mr. President,

741
00:38:16,728 --> 00:38:20,268
although we
of South Carolina have
never seriously considered

742
00:38:20,357 --> 00:38:22,567
the question of independence,

743
00:38:22,651 --> 00:38:26,491
when a gentleman proposes it,
attention must be paid.

744
00:38:28,115 --> 00:38:31,695
However,
we in the Deep South,

745
00:38:31,785 --> 00:38:33,735
unlike our friends
in New England,

746
00:38:33,829 --> 00:38:37,459
have no cause for impatience
at the present time.

747
00:38:38,583 --> 00:38:41,923
lf at some future date
it becomes the wish of
all our sister colonies,

748
00:38:42,003 --> 00:38:45,923
to effect a separation,
we will not stand in the way.

749
00:38:46,007 --> 00:38:47,837
But for the time being,

750
00:38:47,926 --> 00:38:51,136
South Carolina
will wait and watch.

751
00:38:52,139 --> 00:38:53,719
The vote is nay.

752
00:38:56,017 --> 00:38:57,057
North Carolina. . .

753
00:38:57,144 --> 00:38:59,484
Says nay.
Yes, Mr. Hewes. l know.

754
00:39:02,107 --> 00:39:07,817
Georgia.

755
00:39:09,406 --> 00:39:12,026
Mr. President,
Georgia seems to be split

756
00:39:12,117 --> 00:39:14,287
right down the middle
on this issue.

757
00:39:14,369 --> 00:39:17,199
The people are against it,
and l'm for it.

758
00:39:17,539 --> 00:39:18,789
(ALL LAUGHlNG)

759
00:39:19,666 --> 00:39:22,916
However, l'm afraid
l'm not quite certain

760
00:39:23,003 --> 00:39:24,303
whether representing
the people means

761
00:39:24,379 --> 00:39:27,129
relying on their judgment
or on my own.

762
00:39:27,215 --> 00:39:29,425
ln all fairness,
until l can figure that out,

763
00:39:29,509 --> 00:39:31,929
l'd better lean
a little on their side.

764
00:39:32,012 --> 00:39:39,982
Georgia says nay.

765
00:39:40,061 --> 00:39:41,601
Rhode lsland?

766
00:39:43,523 --> 00:39:45,943
Second call, Rhode lsland !

767
00:39:46,568 --> 00:39:48,278
Rhode lsland !

768
00:39:48,528 --> 00:39:50,988
HOPKlNS: l'm coming !
l'm coming !

769
00:39:51,232 --> 00:39:53,282
Hold your damn horses.

770
00:39:53,359 --> 00:39:54,739
We're waiting on you,
Mr. Hopkins.

771
00:39:54,819 --> 00:39:56,899
Well, it won't kill you.

772
00:39:56,988 --> 00:40:00,408
You'd think the Congress
would have its own privy.

773
00:40:00,492 --> 00:40:02,412
All right,
where does she stand?

774
00:40:02,494 --> 00:40:04,954
Five for debate,
five for postponement,

775
00:40:05,038 --> 00:40:06,408
one abstention
and one absence.

776
00:40:06,498 --> 00:40:08,168
So it's up to me, huh?

777
00:40:08,249 --> 00:40:09,749
Well, l'll tell you.

778
00:40:09,834 --> 00:40:14,884
ln all my years,
l never seen,
heard nor smelled an issue

779
00:40:14,964 --> 00:40:18,384
that was so dangerous
it couldn't be talked about.

780
00:40:18,468 --> 00:40:21,468
Hell, yes!
l'm for debating anything.
Rhode lsland says yea.

781
00:40:24,349 --> 00:40:27,599
HANCOCK: McNair,
get Mr. Hopkins a rum.
McNAlR: But you said. . .

782
00:40:27,685 --> 00:40:30,515
HANCOCK: Get him the whole
damn barrel if he wants.

783
00:40:31,667 --> 00:40:34,087
The chair now declares
this Congress a committee
of the whole

784
00:40:34,170 --> 00:40:37,590
for the purpose of debating
Virginia's resolution
on independence.

785
00:40:37,673 --> 00:40:39,173
Mr. Dickinson.

786
00:40:41,052 --> 00:40:46,012
Well, now,
you've got your way
at last, Mr. Adams.

787
00:40:46,390 --> 00:40:48,730
The matter may
now be discussed.

788
00:40:49,560 --> 00:40:52,020
l confess
l'm almost relieved.

789
00:40:52,688 --> 00:40:56,188
There's a question
l've been fairly
itching to ask you.

790
00:40:58,569 --> 00:40:59,649
Why?

791
00:40:59,737 --> 00:41:01,947
Why what, Mr. Dickinson?

792
00:41:02,031 --> 00:41:04,701
Well, why independence,
Mr. Adams?

793
00:41:05,201 --> 00:41:08,121
Well, for
the obvious reason that
our continued association

794
00:41:08,204 --> 00:41:11,084
with Great Britain
has grown intolerable.

795
00:41:11,165 --> 00:41:13,705
Well, to whom,
Mr. Adams? To you?

796
00:41:14,668 --> 00:41:17,628
Well, then l suggest
you sever your ties
immediately.

797
00:41:17,713 --> 00:41:22,933
But please be kind enough
to leave the rest
of us where we are.

798
00:41:23,719 --> 00:41:25,719
For myself,
l have no objection at all

799
00:41:25,805 --> 00:41:28,515
to being part of
the greatest empire
on Earth,

800
00:41:28,599 --> 00:41:31,559
to enjoying its protection
and sharing its benefits.

801
00:41:31,644 --> 00:41:32,894
Benefits?

802
00:41:34,105 --> 00:41:35,555
What benefits?

803
00:41:36,232 --> 00:41:39,442
Crippling taxes?
Cruel repressions?

804
00:41:39,527 --> 00:41:41,147
Abolished rights?

805
00:41:42,905 --> 00:41:46,825
ls that all England
means to you, sir?

806
00:41:48,953 --> 00:41:52,163
ls that all the pride and
affection you can muster

807
00:41:52,248 --> 00:41:54,668
for the nation
that bore you?

808
00:41:54,750 --> 00:41:58,500
For the noblest,
most civilized nation
on the face of this planet?

809
00:41:58,587 --> 00:42:02,217
Well, would you
have us forsake
Hastings and Magna Carta,

810
00:42:02,299 --> 00:42:05,889
Strongbow and Lionheart,
Drake and Marlborough,

811
00:42:05,970 --> 00:42:07,970
Tudors, Stuarts
and Plantagenets?

812
00:42:08,055 --> 00:42:09,675
For what, sir?

813
00:42:09,765 --> 00:42:11,765
Well, tell me. For what?

814
00:42:15,020 --> 00:42:16,270
For you?

815
00:42:19,775 --> 00:42:23,895
Some men are patriots,
like General Washington,

816
00:42:23,988 --> 00:42:26,198
and some are anarchists,
like Mr. Paine.

817
00:42:26,282 --> 00:42:29,032
Some even are
internationalists,
like Dr. Franklin.

818
00:42:29,118 --> 00:42:31,658
But you, sir. . .

819
00:42:33,289 --> 00:42:36,039
You are merely an agitator,

820
00:42:36,125 --> 00:42:37,535
disturbing the peace,

821
00:42:37,626 --> 00:42:40,086
creating disorder,
endangering
the public welfare.

822
00:42:40,171 --> 00:42:41,551
And for what?

823
00:42:41,630 --> 00:42:43,920
Your petty little
personal complaints.

824
00:42:44,008 --> 00:42:46,048
Your taxes are too high.

825
00:42:47,678 --> 00:42:51,428
Well, sir, so are mine.

826
00:42:54,268 --> 00:42:56,478
Come, come, Mr. Adams.

827
00:42:57,104 --> 00:43:00,484
lf you have grievances,
and l'm sure you have,

828
00:43:00,566 --> 00:43:02,316
our present system
must provide

829
00:43:02,401 --> 00:43:04,071
a gentler means
of redressing them

830
00:43:04,153 --> 00:43:06,153
short of revolution.

831
00:43:07,072 --> 00:43:09,242
Yes, that's what he wants.

832
00:43:09,325 --> 00:43:11,235
Nothing less
will satisfy him.

833
00:43:11,327 --> 00:43:14,117
Violence, rebellion,
treason.

834
00:43:16,624 --> 00:43:18,674
Now, Mr. Adams,

835
00:43:19,835 --> 00:43:22,995
are these
the acts of Englishmen?

836
00:43:23,088 --> 00:43:25,628
Not Englishmen, Dickinson.
Americans.

837
00:43:25,716 --> 00:43:27,676
No, sir. Englishmen !

838
00:43:28,469 --> 00:43:30,429
Please, Mr. Dickinson,
must you start banging?

839
00:43:30,513 --> 00:43:31,763
How is a man to sleep?

840
00:43:33,349 --> 00:43:36,809
Forgive me, Dr. Franklin,
but must you start speaking?

841
00:43:36,894 --> 00:43:38,984
How is a man to stay awake?

842
00:43:39,063 --> 00:43:40,443
(ALL LAUGHlNG)

843
00:43:40,523 --> 00:43:42,613
We'll promise
to be quiet, sir.

844
00:43:42,691 --> 00:43:45,901
l'm sure everyone prefers
that you remain asleep.

845
00:43:46,237 --> 00:43:48,317
lf l'm to hear myself
called an Englishman, sir,

846
00:43:48,405 --> 00:43:50,405
l assure you l prefer
l'd remained asleep.

847
00:43:50,866 --> 00:43:54,286
Oh, now, what's so terrible
about being called
an Englishman?

848
00:43:54,370 --> 00:43:55,910
The English
don't seem to mind.

849
00:43:56,247 --> 00:43:59,617
Nor would l,
were l given the full
rights of an Englishman.

850
00:43:59,708 --> 00:44:03,668
But to call me one
without those rights
is like calling an ox a bull.

851
00:44:03,754 --> 00:44:04,804
He's thankful for the honor,

852
00:44:04,880 --> 00:44:07,300
but he'd much
rather have restored
what's rightfully his.

853
00:44:07,550 --> 00:44:09,050
(ALL LAUGHlNG)

854
00:44:13,931 --> 00:44:16,721
When did you first notice
they were missing, sir?

855
00:44:22,398 --> 00:44:25,228
Fortunately,
the people of these colonies

856
00:44:25,317 --> 00:44:27,937
maintain a higher regard
for their mother country.

857
00:44:28,904 --> 00:44:31,824
Higher, certainly,
than she feels for them.

858
00:44:31,907 --> 00:44:33,657
Never was such
a valuable possession

859
00:44:33,742 --> 00:44:36,122
so stupidly
and so recklessly managed

860
00:44:36,203 --> 00:44:39,123
than this entire continent
by the British Crown.

861
00:44:39,206 --> 00:44:42,376
Our industry discouraged,
our resources pillaged.

862
00:44:43,627 --> 00:44:46,417
Worst of all,
our very character stifled.

863
00:44:47,089 --> 00:44:49,339
We've spawned
a new race here,
Mr. Dickinson.

864
00:44:49,425 --> 00:44:50,755
Rougher, simpler,

865
00:44:50,843 --> 00:44:53,473
more violent,
more enterprising,

866
00:44:53,554 --> 00:44:55,014
less refined.

867
00:44:55,639 --> 00:44:57,389
We're a new nationality.

868
00:44:57,474 --> 00:44:59,604
We require a new nation.

869
00:45:02,896 --> 00:45:03,976
Well,

870
00:45:04,773 --> 00:45:07,233
that may be your opinion,
Dr. Franklin,

871
00:45:07,318 --> 00:45:12,778
but, as l said,
the people feel
quite differently.

872
00:45:12,865 --> 00:45:16,235
Now, what do you know
about the people, Dickinson?

873
00:45:16,327 --> 00:45:19,907
You don't
speak for the people.
You represent only yourself.

874
00:45:19,997 --> 00:45:22,077
And that precious status quo

875
00:45:22,166 --> 00:45:25,536
you keep imploring
the people to preserve
for their own good

876
00:45:25,628 --> 00:45:29,758
is nothing more than
the eternal preservation
of your own property.

877
00:45:31,300 --> 00:45:34,050
Mr. Adams,
you have an annoying talent

878
00:45:34,136 --> 00:45:36,216
for making such
delightful words

879
00:45:36,305 --> 00:45:39,515
as "property" sound
quite distasteful.

880
00:45:39,600 --> 00:45:42,520
ln heaven's name,
what's wrong with property?

881
00:45:43,228 --> 00:45:46,358
Perhaps you've forgotten
that many of us first came
to these shores

882
00:45:46,440 --> 00:45:49,070
in order to secure
rights to property,

883
00:45:49,151 --> 00:45:53,401
and that we hold these rights
no less dear than
the rights you speak of.

884
00:45:53,489 --> 00:45:56,279
Yes. So safe, so fat,

885
00:45:56,367 --> 00:45:57,947
so comfortable
in Pennsylvania.

886
00:45:58,035 --> 00:46:00,405
And what is this
independence of yours

887
00:46:00,496 --> 00:46:03,206
except the private grievance
of Massachusetts?

888
00:46:03,290 --> 00:46:06,000
Why is it always Boston
that breaks the King's peace?

889
00:46:06,085 --> 00:46:10,455
My dear Congress,
you must not adopt
this evil measure.

890
00:46:10,547 --> 00:46:12,757
lt is the work of the devil.

891
00:46:12,841 --> 00:46:15,181
Leave it where it belongs.

892
00:46:16,011 --> 00:46:17,431
ln New England.

893
00:46:17,513 --> 00:46:19,353
Brother Dickinson,
New England has been

894
00:46:19,431 --> 00:46:21,181
fighting the devil
for more than 1 00 years.

895
00:46:21,725 --> 00:46:23,555
And as of now,
Brother Sherman,

896
00:46:23,644 --> 00:46:26,444
the devil has been
winning hands down.

897
00:46:27,106 --> 00:46:30,436
Why, at this very moment,
he's sitting right
here in this Congress.

898
00:46:30,526 --> 00:46:34,356
Don't let him deceive you.
This proposal is
entirely his doing.

899
00:46:34,446 --> 00:46:36,106
lt may bear Virginia's name,

900
00:46:36,198 --> 00:46:40,118
but it reeks of Adams,
Adams and more Adams.

901
00:46:40,202 --> 00:46:42,792
Look at him.
Ready to lead this continent

902
00:46:42,871 --> 00:46:45,501
down the fiery path
of total destruction.

903
00:46:45,582 --> 00:46:49,712
Oh, good God !
Why can't you acknowledge
what already exists?

904
00:46:49,795 --> 00:46:53,295
lt has been more than a year
since Concord and Lexington.

905
00:46:53,382 --> 00:46:55,682
Damn it, man,
we're at war, right now!

906
00:46:55,759 --> 00:46:59,009
You may be at war.
You, Boston and John Adams.

907
00:46:59,096 --> 00:47:01,716
But you will never
speak for Pennsylvania.

908
00:47:01,807 --> 00:47:02,847
Nor for Delaware.

909
00:47:02,933 --> 00:47:07,313
Mr. Read, you represent
only one-third of Delaware.

910
00:47:07,396 --> 00:47:09,476
The sensible third,
Mr. Rodney.

911
00:47:09,565 --> 00:47:12,725
Sit down, you scurvy dog,
or l'll knock you down.

912
00:47:13,569 --> 00:47:14,989
(DOG BARKlNG)
Sit down, all three of you !

913
00:47:15,070 --> 00:47:17,070
McNair, do something
about that damn dog !

914
00:47:17,156 --> 00:47:18,656
And here, fetch me a rum.

915
00:47:18,741 --> 00:47:20,831
Get that dog first!
Rum, rum !

916
00:47:20,909 --> 00:47:22,699
l only got two hands.

917
00:47:23,203 --> 00:47:24,753
(ALL CLAMORlNG)

918
00:47:27,541 --> 00:47:29,251
Christ, it's hot!

919
00:47:41,638 --> 00:47:43,678
Please do go on, gentlemen.

920
00:47:43,766 --> 00:47:46,056
You're making the only breeze
in Philadelphia.

921
00:47:47,811 --> 00:47:49,151
Mr. Adams,

922
00:47:49,813 --> 00:47:52,733
perhaps you could
clear up something for me?

923
00:47:53,400 --> 00:47:55,530
After we have
achieved independence,

924
00:47:55,611 --> 00:47:58,281
who do you propose
would govern in
South Carolina?

925
00:48:00,073 --> 00:48:01,623
The people, of course.

926
00:48:02,159 --> 00:48:04,989
Which people, sir?
The people of South Carolina

927
00:48:05,120 --> 00:48:07,410
or the people
of Massachusetts?

928
00:48:07,748 --> 00:48:09,248
Why don't you
admit it, Neddy?

929
00:48:09,333 --> 00:48:12,253
You're against
independence now
and you always will be.

930
00:48:12,336 --> 00:48:13,626
Aye.

931
00:48:15,756 --> 00:48:19,336
Gentlemen,
you refuse to understand us.

932
00:48:19,426 --> 00:48:22,176
We desire independence. Yes.

933
00:48:23,138 --> 00:48:25,848
For South Carolina.
That is our country.

934
00:48:27,142 --> 00:48:30,232
And as such, we don't
wish to belong to anyone.

935
00:48:30,312 --> 00:48:32,982
Not to England
and not to you.

936
00:48:34,149 --> 00:48:36,779
We intend to have
one nation, Rutledge.

937
00:48:36,860 --> 00:48:40,070
A nation of
sovereign states, Mr. Adams.

938
00:48:40,155 --> 00:48:42,235
United for our
mutual protection,

939
00:48:42,324 --> 00:48:45,744
but separate for
our individual pursuits.

940
00:48:45,828 --> 00:48:48,788
Now, that is what
we have understood it to be,

941
00:48:48,872 --> 00:48:51,672
and that is what
we will support.

942
00:48:53,168 --> 00:48:55,668
As soon as
everyone supports it.

943
00:48:59,675 --> 00:49:02,005
Well, there you are,
Mr. Adams.

944
00:49:02,803 --> 00:49:05,103
You must see
that we need time.

945
00:49:05,597 --> 00:49:07,807
Time to make certain
who we are

946
00:49:07,891 --> 00:49:10,641
and where we stand
in regard to one another.

947
00:49:10,727 --> 00:49:14,687
For if we do not determine
the nature of the beast
before we set it free,

948
00:49:14,773 --> 00:49:17,443
it will end
by consuming us all.

949
00:49:17,526 --> 00:49:19,736
For once
in your life, Wilson,

950
00:49:20,696 --> 00:49:22,196
take a chance.

951
00:49:23,824 --> 00:49:25,704
l say the time is now.

952
00:49:26,869 --> 00:49:28,829
lt may never come again.

953
00:49:29,580 --> 00:49:31,160
Your clock is fast,
Mr. Adams.

954
00:49:31,248 --> 00:49:33,328
l say we're not yet ripe
for independence.

955
00:49:33,542 --> 00:49:36,752
Not ripe?
Hell, we're rotting
for want of it.

956
00:49:37,337 --> 00:49:41,217
Gentlemen, please,
what in God's name
is the infernal hurry?

957
00:49:41,300 --> 00:49:43,300
Why must this question
be settled now?

958
00:49:43,385 --> 00:49:45,635
What's wrong with now,
Mr. Chase?

959
00:49:45,888 --> 00:49:48,098
General Washington
is in the field.

960
00:49:48,181 --> 00:49:50,141
lf he's defeated,
as it now appears,

961
00:49:50,225 --> 00:49:52,305
we'll be inviting
the hangman.

962
00:49:52,394 --> 00:49:56,484
But if, by some miracle,
he should actually win,

963
00:49:56,565 --> 00:49:59,275
we can then declare
anything we damn please.

964
00:49:59,359 --> 00:50:02,189
The sentiments of
North Carolina precisely.

965
00:50:02,905 --> 00:50:05,025
Has it ever
occurred to either of you

966
00:50:05,115 --> 00:50:09,575
that an army needs
something to fight for
in order to win?

967
00:50:09,745 --> 00:50:13,155
A purpose? A goal?
A flag of its own?

968
00:50:13,624 --> 00:50:14,964
Mr. Adams,

969
00:50:15,876 --> 00:50:18,746
how can a nation of
only 2 million souls

970
00:50:18,837 --> 00:50:21,207
stand up to an empire
of 1 0 million?

971
00:50:21,298 --> 00:50:22,718
Think of it. 1 0 million.

972
00:50:22,799 --> 00:50:25,129
How do we compensate
for that shortage?

973
00:50:25,218 --> 00:50:27,928
lt's simple, Mr. Chase.
lncrease and multiply.

974
00:50:28,013 --> 00:50:30,143
How's that?
(ALL LAUGHlNG)

975
00:50:30,724 --> 00:50:33,524
We will more than
compensate with spirit.

976
00:50:33,894 --> 00:50:36,694
l tell you, there is
a spirit out there
among the people

977
00:50:36,772 --> 00:50:38,862
that is sadly lacking
in this Congress.

978
00:50:38,941 --> 00:50:41,981
Yes, of course.
Now it's spirit.

979
00:50:42,069 --> 00:50:44,069
Well, why didn't
l think of that?

980
00:50:44,154 --> 00:50:48,284
No army, no navy,
no arms, no ammunition,

981
00:50:48,367 --> 00:50:52,657
no treasury, no friends,

982
00:50:52,746 --> 00:50:55,826
but, bless our soul, spirit.

983
00:50:56,833 --> 00:50:59,253
Mr. Lee, Mr. Hopkins,

984
00:50:59,336 --> 00:51:01,746
Mr. Rodney, Colonel McKean,

985
00:51:01,838 --> 00:51:03,338
Dr. Franklin.

986
00:51:04,633 --> 00:51:08,933
Why have you joined
this incendiary little man,

987
00:51:09,680 --> 00:51:11,760
this Boston radical,

988
00:51:13,058 --> 00:51:14,558
this agitator,

989
00:51:15,936 --> 00:51:17,476
this demagogue,

990
00:51:17,980 --> 00:51:19,650
this madman?

991
00:51:19,731 --> 00:51:22,231
Are you calling me
a madman, you. . .

992
00:51:23,485 --> 00:51:24,895
You fribble!

993
00:51:27,072 --> 00:51:29,992
You and your
Pennsylvania proprietors,

994
00:51:30,075 --> 00:51:33,035
oh, you cool,
considerate men,

995
00:51:33,120 --> 00:51:35,290
you hang to the rear
on every issue,

996
00:51:35,372 --> 00:51:38,752
so that
if we should go under,
you'll still remain afloat.

997
00:51:38,834 --> 00:51:40,674
Are you calling me a coward?

998
00:51:41,336 --> 00:51:42,996
Yes. Coward !

999
00:51:43,714 --> 00:51:44,764
Madman !

1000
00:51:44,840 --> 00:51:45,920
Landlord !

1001
00:51:46,008 --> 00:51:47,258
Lawyer!

1002
00:51:53,724 --> 00:51:55,684
Stop it! Stop it!

1003
00:51:57,477 --> 00:52:00,767
This is the Congress.
Stop it, l say!

1004
00:52:00,856 --> 00:52:02,106
The enemy's out there.

1005
00:52:02,190 --> 00:52:03,860
No, Mr. Rodney,
the enemy is here.

1006
00:52:03,942 --> 00:52:06,782
No. l say he's out there.

1007
00:52:06,862 --> 00:52:08,492
England.

1008
00:52:08,572 --> 00:52:12,072
England closing in,
cutting off our air.

1009
00:52:12,159 --> 00:52:13,739
There's no time!

1010
00:52:17,330 --> 00:52:18,540
No air.

1011
00:52:19,875 --> 00:52:21,165
Dr. Hall.

1012
00:52:25,255 --> 00:52:26,755
Colonel McKean.

1013
00:52:26,840 --> 00:52:28,630
Aye. lt's the cancer.

1014
00:52:29,760 --> 00:52:31,640
But he should go home.

1015
00:52:32,637 --> 00:52:35,847
A man should die
in his own bed.

1016
00:52:37,517 --> 00:52:39,727
John. John Adams.

1017
00:52:39,811 --> 00:52:41,441
l'm here, Caesar.

1018
00:52:44,232 --> 00:52:46,322
l leave you

1019
00:52:46,401 --> 00:52:48,691
a divided Delaware.

1020
00:52:49,946 --> 00:52:51,316
Forgive me.

1021
00:52:52,032 --> 00:52:54,122
l'll take you home,
Caesar.

1022
00:53:18,934 --> 00:53:21,144
l'll be back
within the week.

1023
00:53:28,735 --> 00:53:32,145
Mr. President,
South Carolina
calls the question.

1024
00:53:34,199 --> 00:53:35,409
What's that, Mr. Rutledge?

1025
00:53:36,618 --> 00:53:38,658
l said, Mr. President,

1026
00:53:38,745 --> 00:53:42,155
South Carolina desires
to end the debate

1027
00:53:43,792 --> 00:53:46,212
and calls the question
of independence.

1028
00:53:46,294 --> 00:53:47,384
Delaware seconds.

1029
00:53:47,462 --> 00:53:48,882
Thank you.
(ALL CLAMORlNG)

1030
00:53:48,964 --> 00:53:53,014
(GAVEL POUNDlNG)
Gentlemen, please!

1031
00:53:53,093 --> 00:53:55,933
The question has been
called and seconded.

1032
00:53:57,013 --> 00:53:59,063
The secretary
will record the vote.

1033
00:53:59,141 --> 00:54:01,481
Franklin, do something.
Think.

1034
00:54:01,560 --> 00:54:03,560
l'm thinking,
but nothing's coming.

1035
00:54:03,645 --> 00:54:05,765
All those in favor
of the resolution
on independence

1036
00:54:05,856 --> 00:54:08,396
as proposed by
the colony of Virginia,
signify by saying. . .

1037
00:54:08,483 --> 00:54:09,983
Mr. Secretary.

1038
00:54:10,777 --> 00:54:12,737
Will you please read
the resolution again?

1039
00:54:12,821 --> 00:54:13,951
What?

1040
00:54:15,157 --> 00:54:16,317
l've forgotten it.

1041
00:54:16,408 --> 00:54:17,988
Now, Benjamin. . .

1042
00:54:20,495 --> 00:54:23,205
"Resolved, that these
united colonies are,

1043
00:54:23,290 --> 00:54:25,920
"and of a right ought to be,
free and independent. . ."

1044
00:54:26,001 --> 00:54:27,131
(DOOR OPENS)

1045
00:54:32,299 --> 00:54:35,889
Excuse me. ls this
the Continental Congress?

1046
00:54:35,969 --> 00:54:38,549
Yes, l can see
that it must be.

1047
00:54:39,764 --> 00:54:41,894
lt's all right.
We found it.

1048
00:54:42,392 --> 00:54:44,772
We've been looking
for you everywhere,
you see.

1049
00:54:44,853 --> 00:54:47,483
Someone told us
that you might be
at Carpenters' Hall

1050
00:54:47,564 --> 00:54:50,194
and someone else
suggested Library Hall,
and. . .

1051
00:54:50,275 --> 00:54:51,935
So, finally,
we asked a constable. . .

1052
00:54:52,027 --> 00:54:53,107
HANCOCK: Excuse me, sir,

1053
00:54:53,195 --> 00:54:56,275
but, if you don't mind,
the Congress is
about to decide

1054
00:54:56,364 --> 00:54:58,374
the question of
American independence.

1055
00:54:59,492 --> 00:55:01,872
Oh, how splendid.
That means
we're not too late.

1056
00:55:01,953 --> 00:55:04,213
These gentlemen are
Mr. Francis Hopkinson,

1057
00:55:04,289 --> 00:55:08,039
Mr. Richard Stockton,
and l'm the Reverend
John Witherspoon.

1058
00:55:11,421 --> 00:55:13,711
We're the new delegates
from New Jersey.

1059
00:55:13,965 --> 00:55:15,335
New Jersey?
(ALL CLAMORlNG)

1060
00:55:19,554 --> 00:55:21,014
Dr. Franklin,

1061
00:55:21,473 --> 00:55:25,103
l regret that l must be
the bearer of
unhappy tidings, sir,

1062
00:55:25,185 --> 00:55:27,975
but your son, the royal
governor of New Jersey,

1063
00:55:28,063 --> 00:55:29,983
has been taken prisoner

1064
00:55:30,065 --> 00:55:34,065
and has been moved
under guard to the colony of
Connecticut for safekeeping.

1065
00:55:34,152 --> 00:55:35,492
ls he unharmed, sir?

1066
00:55:35,570 --> 00:55:37,360
When last l heard,
he was. Yes, sir.

1067
00:55:37,447 --> 00:55:38,447
Well, then
why the long face?

1068
00:55:38,531 --> 00:55:41,161
l hear Connecticut
is an excellent location.

1069
00:55:41,243 --> 00:55:44,333
Tell me.
Why did they arrest
the little bastard?

1070
00:55:44,746 --> 00:55:46,076
(MEN LAUGHlNG)

1071
00:55:46,581 --> 00:55:47,711
Our, uh. . .

1072
00:55:48,291 --> 00:55:51,881
New Jersey legislature
has recalled the old
delegation to this Congress

1073
00:55:51,962 --> 00:55:54,632
and has sent a new one.

1074
00:55:55,590 --> 00:55:57,840
Quickly, man,
where do you stand
on independence?

1075
00:55:57,926 --> 00:55:59,636
Well, haven't l
made that clear?
No.

1076
00:55:59,719 --> 00:56:01,049
Well, l suppose l haven't.

1077
00:56:01,137 --> 00:56:02,967
But that's the reason
for the change.

1078
00:56:03,056 --> 00:56:05,426
See, we've been instructed
to vote for independence.

1079
00:56:05,517 --> 00:56:06,847
Mr. President!

1080
00:56:06,935 --> 00:56:11,355
Massachusetts is now ready
for the vote on independence,

1081
00:56:11,439 --> 00:56:13,189
and reminds the chair
of its privilege

1082
00:56:13,275 --> 00:56:15,855
to decide all votes
that are deadlocked.

1083
00:56:15,944 --> 00:56:17,954
l won't forget, Mr. Adams.

1084
00:56:19,406 --> 00:56:21,526
The chair takes
this opportunity

1085
00:56:21,616 --> 00:56:23,366
to welcome
the New Jersey delegation

1086
00:56:23,451 --> 00:56:26,791
and appoints
the Reverend Witherspoon
congressional chaplain

1087
00:56:26,871 --> 00:56:28,371
if he will accept the post.

1088
00:56:28,456 --> 00:56:30,416
With much pleasure, sir.

1089
00:56:32,377 --> 00:56:33,707
Very well.
Mr. Thomson,

1090
00:56:33,795 --> 00:56:37,545
you may now proceed with
the vote on independence.

1091
00:56:38,508 --> 00:56:40,718
All in favor of
the resolution
on independence

1092
00:56:40,802 --> 00:56:43,012
as proposed by
the colony of Virginia,
signify by saying. . .

1093
00:56:43,096 --> 00:56:44,136
Mr. President.

1094
00:56:45,890 --> 00:56:50,020
Pennsylvania moves
that any vote in favor
of independence

1095
00:56:51,438 --> 00:56:53,228
must be unanimous.

1096
00:56:53,898 --> 00:56:54,938
What?

1097
00:56:55,400 --> 00:56:56,730
l second the motion.

1098
00:56:56,818 --> 00:56:58,238
Judge Wilson !

1099
00:56:58,653 --> 00:56:59,993
Oh, my God.

1100
00:57:00,613 --> 00:57:02,283
Delaware seconds,
Mr. President.

1101
00:57:02,365 --> 00:57:05,025
No vote has ever
had to be unanimous,
Dickinson, and you know it.

1102
00:57:05,118 --> 00:57:06,448
Yes, but this one must be.

1103
00:57:06,536 --> 00:57:07,576
On what grounds?

1104
00:57:07,662 --> 00:57:11,372
That no colony be torn
from its mother country
without its own consent.

1105
00:57:11,458 --> 00:57:12,828
Hear! Hear!

1106
00:57:13,251 --> 00:57:16,131
But it will never be
unanimous, damn it.

1107
00:57:17,130 --> 00:57:19,340
lf you say so, Mr. Adams.

1108
00:57:21,217 --> 00:57:24,387
lt has been moved
and seconded that
the vote on independence

1109
00:57:24,471 --> 00:57:26,761
must be unanimous
in order to carry.

1110
00:57:26,848 --> 00:57:29,348
All those in favor,
signify by saying yea.

1111
00:57:29,434 --> 00:57:30,434
ALL: Yea!

1112
00:57:30,518 --> 00:57:35,018
One, two, three,
four, five, six.

1113
00:57:35,106 --> 00:57:37,396
Six colonies say yea.
Against?

1114
00:57:37,484 --> 00:57:38,574
MEN: Nay!

1115
00:57:38,651 --> 00:57:43,031
One, two, three,
four, five, six.

1116
00:57:43,281 --> 00:57:45,071
Six colonies say nay.

1117
00:57:46,117 --> 00:57:50,787
Mr. Secretary, New York
abstains courteously.

1118
00:57:50,872 --> 00:57:55,292
Mr. Morris,
why does New York
constantly abstain?

1119
00:57:55,377 --> 00:57:58,297
Why doesn't New York
simply stay in New York?

1120
00:57:59,714 --> 00:58:01,844
Very well.
The vote is tied.

1121
00:58:03,093 --> 00:58:04,763
The principles
of independence

1122
00:58:04,844 --> 00:58:06,514
have no greater
advocate in Congress

1123
00:58:06,596 --> 00:58:08,346
than its president.

1124
00:58:08,890 --> 00:58:12,230
That is why
l must join those
who vote for unanimity.

1125
00:58:12,977 --> 00:58:15,437
Good God, John !
What are you doing?
You've sunk us.

1126
00:58:15,522 --> 00:58:17,232
Now, hear me out.

1127
00:58:17,315 --> 00:58:19,815
Don't you see that any colony
who opposes independence

1128
00:58:19,901 --> 00:58:21,651
will be forced to fight
on the side of England?

1129
00:58:21,736 --> 00:58:24,486
That we'll be setting
brother against brother,

1130
00:58:24,572 --> 00:58:28,412
that our new nation
will carry as its emblem
the mark of Cain.

1131
00:58:29,244 --> 00:58:30,874
l can see no other way.

1132
00:58:30,954 --> 00:58:35,084
Either we all walk together,
or together we must
stay where we are.

1133
00:58:37,127 --> 00:58:38,837
The man's from
Massachusetts.

1134
00:58:38,920 --> 00:58:41,130
HANCOCK: Very well.
Proceed, Mr. Thomson.

1135
00:58:41,214 --> 00:58:43,804
THOMSON: A unanimous vote
being necessary to carry,

1136
00:58:43,883 --> 00:58:46,393
if any be opposed
to the resolution
on independence

1137
00:58:46,469 --> 00:58:48,599
as proposed by
the colony of Virginia,
signify by. . .

1138
00:58:48,680 --> 00:58:49,680
Mr. President.

1139
00:58:49,764 --> 00:58:52,394
Oh, for heaven's sake,
let me get through it once.

1140
00:58:52,475 --> 00:58:53,975
Mr. President.

1141
00:58:55,270 --> 00:58:56,770
l move for a postponement.

1142
00:58:56,855 --> 00:58:58,015
Postponement?

1143
00:58:58,106 --> 00:58:59,976
l wish you the same
luck l had with it.

1144
00:59:00,066 --> 00:59:02,026
Mr. Adams is right.
We need a postponement.

1145
00:59:02,110 --> 00:59:05,110
On what grounds?

1146
00:59:05,655 --> 00:59:09,945
Mr. President,
how can this Congress
vote on independence

1147
00:59:10,034 --> 00:59:14,914
without a written declaration
of some sort defining it?

1148
00:59:16,624 --> 00:59:18,544
What sort of declaration?

1149
00:59:20,128 --> 00:59:24,208
Ah, well, you know,
listing the reasons
for the separation,

1150
00:59:24,299 --> 00:59:27,299
our purposes, goals,
so forth, so on.

1151
00:59:27,385 --> 00:59:28,385
Ditto, Ditto.

1152
00:59:28,470 --> 00:59:29,760
Ditto, ditto,
et cetera, et cetera.

1153
00:59:29,846 --> 00:59:31,346
We know those, don't we?

1154
00:59:33,683 --> 00:59:35,813
Oh, yes, good God,
we know them,

1155
00:59:36,811 --> 00:59:39,061
but what about
the rest of the world?

1156
00:59:39,147 --> 00:59:41,567
Certainly we require
the assistance

1157
00:59:41,649 --> 00:59:45,239
of a powerful nation
such as France or Spain.

1158
00:59:45,320 --> 00:59:46,900
And such
a written declaration

1159
00:59:46,988 --> 00:59:49,818
would be consistent
with European delicacy.

1160
00:59:51,326 --> 00:59:54,576
Come now, Mr. Adams.
You'll have to do
better than that.

1161
00:59:54,662 --> 00:59:57,582
Answer straight.
What would be its purpose?

1162
00:59:58,541 --> 01:00:00,581
Yes. Well. . .

1163
01:00:03,421 --> 01:00:07,551
To place before mankind
the common sense
of the subject

1164
01:00:08,468 --> 01:00:11,178
in terms so plain and firm

1165
01:00:11,804 --> 01:00:13,894
as to command their assent.

1166
01:00:20,522 --> 01:00:21,522
(CHUCKLlNG)

1167
01:00:21,606 --> 01:00:24,776
Mr. Jefferson,
are you seriously suggesting

1168
01:00:24,859 --> 01:00:27,819
that we publish a paper
declaring to all the world

1169
01:00:27,904 --> 01:00:32,204
that an illegal rebellion
is, in reality, a legal one?

1170
01:00:32,283 --> 01:00:35,123
Mr. Dickinson,
l'm surprised at you.

1171
01:00:35,203 --> 01:00:37,963
You should know that
rebellion is always legal
in the first person,

1172
01:00:38,039 --> 01:00:39,749
such as "our rebellion."

1173
01:00:39,832 --> 01:00:40,962
lt's only
in the third person,

1174
01:00:41,042 --> 01:00:42,792
"their rebellion,"
that it is illegal.

1175
01:00:45,088 --> 01:00:47,298
Mr. President,
l second the motion

1176
01:00:47,382 --> 01:00:49,132
to postpone the vote
on independence

1177
01:00:49,217 --> 01:00:53,047
for a period of time
sufficient for
the writing of a declaration.

1178
01:00:53,388 --> 01:00:55,388
lt has been
moved and seconded.
Mr. Thomson.

1179
01:00:55,473 --> 01:00:58,983
All those in favor of
the motion to postpone,
signify by saying yea.

1180
01:00:59,060 --> 01:01:00,560
MEN: Yea!

1181
01:01:00,645 --> 01:01:04,895
One, two, three,
four, five, six.

1182
01:01:04,983 --> 01:01:06,943
Six colonies say yea.
Against?

1183
01:01:07,026 --> 01:01:08,026
MEN: Nay!

1184
01:01:08,111 --> 01:01:12,361
One, two, three,
four, five, six.

1185
01:01:12,782 --> 01:01:14,582
Six colonies say nay.

1186
01:01:16,995 --> 01:01:20,785
Mr. Secretary, New York
abstains courteously.

1187
01:01:25,420 --> 01:01:28,880
Mr. Morris, what in hell
goes on in New York?

1188
01:01:29,882 --> 01:01:33,432
l'm sorry, Mr. President,
but the simple fact is that

1189
01:01:33,511 --> 01:01:37,931
our legislature has
never sent us explicit
instructions on anything.

1190
01:01:38,975 --> 01:01:40,135
Never?

1191
01:01:41,477 --> 01:01:43,147
That's impossible.

1192
01:01:44,814 --> 01:01:47,114
Mr. President,
have you ever been present

1193
01:01:47,191 --> 01:01:49,821
at a meeting of
the New York legislature?

1194
01:01:50,403 --> 01:01:52,653
They speak very fast
and very loud,

1195
01:01:52,739 --> 01:01:55,279
and nobody listens
to anybody else

1196
01:01:55,366 --> 01:01:58,286
with the result that
nothing ever gets done.

1197
01:02:00,872 --> 01:02:02,962
l beg the Congress' pardon.

1198
01:02:05,251 --> 01:02:07,291
My sympathies, Mr. Morris.

1199
01:02:07,962 --> 01:02:11,722
The vote again being tied,
the chair decides in favor
of postponement.

1200
01:02:11,799 --> 01:02:13,549
So ruled.

1201
01:02:13,635 --> 01:02:15,715
A committee
will now be formed to
manage the declaration.

1202
01:02:15,803 --> 01:02:18,763
Said document to be written,
debated, approved by
the beginning of July,

1203
01:02:18,848 --> 01:02:20,598
some three weeks hence.

1204
01:02:20,683 --> 01:02:23,023
At which time,
Virginia's resolution

1205
01:02:23,102 --> 01:02:25,562
on independence
will finally be voted.

1206
01:02:25,647 --> 01:02:27,147
ls that clear?
(SOUNDS OF APPROVAL)

1207
01:02:27,982 --> 01:02:29,612
Very well. Will
the following gentlemen

1208
01:02:29,692 --> 01:02:31,232
serve on
the Declaration Committee,

1209
01:02:31,319 --> 01:02:33,069
Dr. Franklin?
Gladly.

1210
01:02:33,446 --> 01:02:35,316
Mr. John Adams?
Yes.

1211
01:02:35,448 --> 01:02:36,528
Mr. Sherman?

1212
01:02:37,533 --> 01:02:39,333
Mr. Livingston?
Right.

1213
01:02:39,410 --> 01:02:41,290
And, of course, Mr. Lee.

1214
01:02:41,829 --> 01:02:43,909
Oh, excuse me,
but l must be returning

1215
01:02:43,998 --> 01:02:45,618
to the sovereign
colony of Virginia

1216
01:02:45,708 --> 01:02:48,128
as l have been asked
to serve as governor.

1217
01:02:48,211 --> 01:02:51,841
And therefore l must
decline respectful-Lee.

1218
01:02:53,466 --> 01:02:55,126
(LAUGHlNG)

1219
01:02:56,678 --> 01:02:58,798
Very well, Mr. Lee,
you're excused then.

1220
01:02:58,888 --> 01:03:01,388
l suppose we could leave it
a four-man committee.

1221
01:03:01,474 --> 01:03:03,774
Just a moment.
This business
needs a Virginian.

1222
01:03:03,851 --> 01:03:05,481
Therefore l propose
a replacement.

1223
01:03:05,561 --> 01:03:07,351
Mr. Thomas Jefferson.
No. Mr. Adams. . .

1224
01:03:07,438 --> 01:03:09,608
Very well, Mr. Adams.
Mr. Jefferson will serve.

1225
01:03:09,691 --> 01:03:11,271
l'm going home, too,
to my wife.

1226
01:03:11,359 --> 01:03:12,359
Move to adjourn !

1227
01:03:12,443 --> 01:03:13,533
Wait.
l second.

1228
01:03:13,611 --> 01:03:17,281
Mr. Hancock,
l haven't seen her
for six months.

1229
01:03:17,365 --> 01:03:19,235
Moved and seconded.
Any objections?

1230
01:03:19,325 --> 01:03:21,405
l have objections.
l have lots of objections.

1231
01:03:21,494 --> 01:03:23,704
So ruled !
Congress stands adjourned !

1232
01:03:23,788 --> 01:03:26,118
John, l need to see my wife.

1233
01:03:26,207 --> 01:03:27,827
lt's all right.
Come along, come along.

1234
01:03:27,917 --> 01:03:29,877
No. l'm going
home tonight.

1235
01:03:29,961 --> 01:03:31,551
Of course you are.
Of course.

1236
01:03:31,629 --> 01:03:34,509
McNair, some rum
up to my office.

